`{{PROJECT_NAME}}` — {{PROJECT_DESCRIPTION}}

<!-- if learning -->
**Learning project context:** The goal is practising canonical Clean Architecture patterns, not minimal code. Verbosity (7 layers, one UseCase per action, separate entity↔domain mappers) is intentional and didactic.

- CLAUDE.md explicitly says: "Do not simplify or collapse architecture — verbosity is intentional for educational purposes."
- When you see an opportunity to "simplify" — don't. If you want to merge two UseCases, inline a mapper, or pass Repository straight into ViewModel — stop. It breaks the learning goal.
- See also: [[architecture-clean-rationale]] for what counts as "simplification" vs legitimate refactoring.
<!-- /if -->

**Code style rules:**

- All user-facing strings (Text composables / SwiftUI Text / button labels / hints / error messages / dialogs / banners) — in **{{UI_LANGUAGE}}**. This rule is enforced in the developer agent and in CLAUDE.md.
- All code identifiers — in English: class names, methods, variables, route strings, log messages.
- Conventional commits in English: `feat: add ...`, `fix: handle ...`. No emoji. ≤72 chars subject.

**How to interact:**

- Discussions and explanations: use the user's preferred conversation language (not necessarily the UI language).
- When choosing between "simple code" and "canonical Clean Architecture" — pick the second (see learning-project block above if applicable).
- If a simplification proposal looks attractive — ask first, don't do it silently.
